      <div xml:id="NA266-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu talaimakaṉaic celavu uṭampaṭṭatu (EN, ER, ET, EV: uṭaṉpaṭṭatu). 2. kaṭinakar varaippiṉ kaṇṭu makiḻnta talaimakaṟkut tōḻi “nummālē āyiṟṟu” eṉṟu colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is [making] HIM agree to going. 2. This is how the confidante said “[this] has happened because of you” to HIM who was delighted when seeing [her] within the confines of the protected mansion.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA266">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kollaik kōvalar kuṟumpuṉañ cērnta</l>
<l>            kuṟuṅkāṟ kuraviṉ kuviyiṇar vāṉpū</l>
<l>            vāṭuṭai yiṭaimakaṉ cūṭap pūkku</l>
<l>            makalu ḷāṇkaṭ cīṟū rēmē</l>
<l>            yatuvē cāluva kāma maṉṟiyu </l>
<l>            memviṭ ṭakaṟi rāyiṟ koṉṉoṉṟu</l>
<l>            kūṟuval vāḻiya raiya vēṟupaṭ</l>
<l>            ṭirīiya kālai yiriyiṟ</l>
<l>            periya vallavō periyavar nilaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>We [are] in [our] small village, that place wide inside,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the sky flowers of the short-trunked Kura-tree bloom</l>
<l rend="indent2">in piling clusters, close to the small fields of the cowherds,<note place="foot">What kind of relation is intended between the <term xml:lang="ta">kōvalar</term> and the <term xml:lang="ta">iṭaimakaṉ</term>? Is this a movement from centre to periphery?</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">in the clearing, to be worn by the shepherd-son with [his] sheep.</l>
<l>That alone is worthy<note place="foot">Here we are faced with a problem of deciding between the variants. Strictly morphologically speaking, <term xml:lang="ta">cālum</term> (n.sg.) is the only possibility, for <term xml:lang="ta">atu</term> requires a sg. predicate. This seems to be, however, a simplification, since nearly all of the other testimonies read <term xml:lang="ta">cāluva</term> (n.pl.). We might consider whether the <term xml:lang="ta">atu</term> is meant anaphoric rather than cataphoric, i.e. referring to THEIR staying in the village, while the additional quality is the state of fortitude, so that <term xml:lang="ta">nilai</term> would be the second subject.</note>, even apart from desire:</l>
<l>If you depart, deserting us, I tell</l>
<l>you one thing<note place="foot">The strange proclithic particle <term xml:lang="ta">koṉ</term> is here explained by T.V.G. as "futility".</note>, may you live, lord:</l>
<l rend="indent4">if the time</l>
<l rend="indent3">that made us wait, changing<note place="foot">T.V.G. here connects <term xml:lang="ta">vērupaṭṭu</term> with HIM and takes it as going away. If we think of the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term> idiom connected with this word this seems rather unlikely.</note>, retreats,</l>
<l>won’t the state of the great ones be great?<note place="foot">As usual, the message seems to be double-bound: certainly SHE will undergo the usual symptoms during HIS absence, but once he comes back she will receive him with fortitude as is befitting.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
